    <li data-comment-id="comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/1858-411-303" data-comment-wp-id="303" class="comment level0 calledOut">
    	<div class="user_block">
						<!-- Comment ID is comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/1858-411-303 -->
            <!-- Integer Comment ID is 303 -->
			<!-- Comment parent ID is $comment.parentCommentId -->
			<!-- Comment publishDate is Fri Mar 02 14:24:06 EST 2012 -->

			        		<a class="avatar" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/produceconsume/">
    				    					<img src="http://blogs-images.forbes.com/cache/gravatars/produceconsume_40.jpg" alt="lisasroberts" />
    				        		</a>
			
			               	<a class="user_name" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/produceconsume/">lisasroberts</a>
            
    		



    		
    		    		<span class="timestamp">4 days ago</span>
    	</div>

    	<div class="comment_content">
    		<p>Carolyn:</p>
<p>Our End-of-Life Twitter chat (#EOLChat) group recently discussed this article as well. We were no doubt part of the Twittersphere activity you refer to in your post.</p>
<p>One of the lines that really stood out to me from Dr. Murray&#8217;s article was &#8220;life of quality.&#8221;  I shared this with our chat group.  Many of us felt as though it resonated more so than &#8220;quality of life&#8221;  &#8211; which feels more like a reactive measure of outcome.  Life of quality speaks to what we want done now.  It is more proactive and empowering than the QOL acronym of which we&#8217;ve become familiar.</p>
<p>I applaud you for including end-of-life discussion as part of your counseling. More advisors need to be including this in their conversations &#8211; more physicians, health care providers, caregivers, family, and friends.  I am honestly surprised that CMS has not raised the visibility of these discussions more in the mainstream media and beyond.</p>
<p>As for my end of life choices? I&#8217;ve plagiarized part of my wishes from my tweep, @KathyKastner: &#8220;Tequila and chocolate-covered almonds are in my advanced directive.&#8221;</p>
<p>End of Life = Part of Life. Again thank you for highlighting this discussion.</p>
<p>Lisa</p>

    	</div>

